<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Chemical Reactions <span class="punjabi">(ਰਸਾਇਣਕ ਕਿਰਿਆਵਾਂ)</span></h2>
                <p>A chemical reaction means <span class="accent">new substances are formed</span> <span class="punjabi">(ਨਵੇਂ ਪਦਾਰਥ ਬਣਦੇ ਹਨ)</span>.</p>
                <table>
                    <tr>
                        <th>Reactants <span class="punjabi">(ਅਭਿਕਾਰਕ)</span></th>
                        <th>Products <span class="punjabi">(ਉਤਪਾਦ)</span></th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Starting substances. The things that react together.</td>
                        <td>New substances formed after the reaction.</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>
                <p><strong>Example:</strong> Magnesium + Oxygen &rarr; Magnesium oxide</p>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>NCERT Activity 1.1: Magnesium Ribbon</h2>
                <div class="lab-box">
                    <h3>🧪 Practical Lab Guide</h3>
                    <p><strong>Action:</strong> Burning a Magnesium Ribbon in air.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Observation:</strong> It burns with a <strong>dazzling white flame</strong>.</li>
                        <li><strong>Result:</strong> The ash left behind is a <strong>white powder</strong> called Magnesium Oxide ($MgO$).</li>
                        <li><strong>Caution:</strong> Clean the ribbon with sandpaper first to remove the protective layer of basic magnesium carbonate.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <div class="equation">2Mg(s) + O₂(g) &rarr; 2MgO(s)</div>
                </div>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>NCERT Activity 1.2: Precipitation</h2>
                <div class="lab-box">
                    <h3>🧪 Practical Lab Guide</h3>
                    <p><strong>Action:</strong> Mix aqueous solutions of Lead Nitrate and Potassium Iodide.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Observation:</strong> A sudden color change to yellow.</li>
                        <li><strong>Result:</strong> A <strong>yellow precipitate</strong> (solid) of Lead Iodide ($PbI_2$) is formed.</li>
                        <li><strong>Reaction Type:</strong> Double Displacement & Precipitation.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <div class="equation">Pb(NO₃)₂(aq) + 2KI(aq) &rarr; PbI₂(s)↓ + 2KNO₃(aq)</div>
                </div>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>NCERT Activity 1.3: Evolution of Gas</h2>
                <div class="lab-box">
                    <h3>🧪 Practical Lab Guide</h3>
                    <p><strong>Action:</strong> Add dilute Sulphuric Acid ($H_2SO_4$) to Zinc granules in a conical flask.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Observation:</strong> Bubbles form rapidly around the zinc. The flask becomes <strong>hot to the touch</strong> (Exothermic).</li>
                        <li><strong>Result:</strong> Hydrogen gas ($H_2$) is evolved.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <div class="equation">Zn(s) + H₂SO₄(aq) &rarr; ZnSO₄(aq) + H₂(g)&uarr;</div>
                </div>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Word Equation vs. Skeletal Equation <span class="punjabi">(ਸ਼ਬਦ ਸਮੀਕਰਣ ਅਤੇ ਢਾਂਚਾ ਸਮੀਕਰਣ)</span></h2>
                <p>A chemical reaction can be written in two ways:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Word Equation <span class="punjabi">(ਸ਼ਬਦ ਸਮੀਕਰਣ)</span>:</strong> Uses names of chemicals.<br>
                        <em>Example: Magnesium + Oxygen &rarr; Magnesium oxide</em>
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>Skeletal Equation <span class="punjabi">(ਢਾਂਚਾ ਸਮੀਕਰਣ)</span>:</strong> Uses chemical formulas, but is NOT balanced yet.<br>
                        <em>Example: Mg + O₂ &rarr; MgO</em>
                    </li>
                </ul>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Physical States in Equations <span class="punjabi">(ਭੌਤਿਕ ਅਵਸਥਾਵਾਂ)</span></h2>
                <p>To make equations more informative, we write the physical states of reactants and products.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>(s)</strong> = Solid <span class="punjabi">(ਠੋਸ)</span></li>
                    <li><strong>(l)</strong> = Liquid <span class="punjabi">(ਤਰਲ)</span></li>
                    <li><strong>(g)</strong> = Gas <span class="punjabi">(ਗੈਸ)</span></li>
                    <li><strong>(aq)</strong> = Aqueous (dissolved in water) <span class="punjabi">(ਜਲਮਈ ਘੋਲ)</span></li>
                </ul>
                <div class="equation">Ca(OH)₂(aq) + CO₂(g) &rarr; CaCO₃(s)↓ + H₂O(l)</div>
                <p><em>Note: The ↓ arrow also indicates a precipitate (solid) was formed! The &uarr; arrow indicates a gas.</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Reaction Prediction Flowchart <span class="punjabi">(ਕਿਰਿਆ ਦੀ ਭਵਿੱਖਬਾਣੀ)</span></h2>
                <p>Don't just memorize! Ask yourself these questions to find the reaction type:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Are two elements combining into one? &rarr; <strong>Combination</strong></li>
                    <li>Is there only ONE reactant being heated? &rarr; <strong>Decomposition</strong></li>
                    <li>Is it a single element reacting with a compound? &rarr; <strong>Displacement</strong></li>
                    <li>Are two compounds exchanging ions? &rarr; <strong>Double Displacement</strong></li>
                </ul>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Decomposition Specifics (3 Marks) <span class="pyq-tag">PSEB 2018, 2021, 2023</span></h2>
                <p>Because decomposition reactions require energy to break bonds, they are always <strong>Endothermic</strong>. The energy comes in three forms:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Thermal (Heat):</strong> Heating limestone.<br><span class="equation">CaCO₃(s) + Heat &rarr; CaO(s) + CO₂(g)</span></li>
                    <li><strong>Electrolytic (Electricity):</strong> Splitting water.<br><span class="equation">2H₂O(l) + Electricity &rarr; 2H₂(g) + O₂(g)</span></li>
                    <li><strong>Photolytic (Light):</strong> Used in black & white photography.<br><span class="equation">2AgCl(s) + Sunlight &rarr; 2Ag(s) + Cl₂(g)</span></li>
                </ul>
                <div class="pitfall-box">
                    <h3>🚨 Board Exam Pitfall</h3>
                    <p>If the exam asks you to identify the reaction "2AgCl &rarr; 2Ag + Cl₂", do NOT just write "Decomposition". You must write <strong>"Photolytic Decomposition"</strong> to get full marks!</p>
                </div>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Oxidation & Reduction <span class="punjabi">(ਆਕਸੀਕਰਨ ਅਤੇ ਲਘੂਕਰਨ)</span></h2>
                <p>These reactions happen together (Redox reactions).</p>
                <table>
                    <tr>
                        <th>Oxidation <span class="punjabi">(ਆਕਸੀਕਰਨ)</span></th>
                        <th>Reduction <span class="punjabi">(ਲਘੂਕਰਨ)</span></th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Gains Oxygen <span class="accent-blue">(+O)</span> OR Loses Hydrogen <span class="accent">(-H)</span></td>
                        <td>Loses Oxygen <span class="accent">(-O)</span> OR Gains Hydrogen <span class="accent-blue">(+H)</span></td>
                    </tr>
                </table>
                <div class="template-box">
                    <h3>📋 Finding the Agent Trick</h3>
                    <p>The substance that is <strong>oxidized</strong> is the <em>Reducing Agent</em>. The substance that is <strong>reduced</strong> is the <em>Oxidizing Agent</em>. (They are opposites!)</p>
                </div>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Oxidation Tracking (Example)</h2>
                <p>Identify the oxidized/reduced substances and agents in:</p>
                <div class="equation">CuO + H₂ &rarr; Cu + H₂O</div>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>CuO</strong> loses oxygen to become Cu. It is <strong>Reduced</strong>. Therefore, CuO is the <em>Oxidizing Agent</em>.</li>
                    <li><strong>H₂</strong> gains oxygen to become H₂O. It is <strong>Oxidized</strong>. Therefore, H₂ is the <em>Reducing Agent</em>.</li>
                </ul>
</div></div>
