        <h3 style="margin-top:0; color: var(--goku-blue); font-size: 2rem;">The Silent Destroyers</h3>
        <div class="reading-text" id="read-ch1c">Oxidation is not always a violent fire; sometimes it is a slow, silent thief. When iron is exposed to the moisture in the air, a reddish-brown flaky crust forms on its surface. This is rust, and it eats away at bridges, ships, and car bodies, causing billions of dollars in damage globally every year. Similarly, when fats and oils in our food are left in the open, they oxidize and turn rancid, completely changing their smell and taste. To fight this silent destruction, we coat our metals in zinc and flush our potato chip bags with nitrogen gas, desperately trying to keep the oxygen away.</div>
