                <h2>Physical States in Equations <span class="punjabi">(ਭੌਤਿਕ ਅਵਸਥਾਵਾਂ)</span></h2>
                <p>To make equations more informative, we write the physical states of reactants and products.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>(s)</strong> = Solid <span class="punjabi">(ਠੋਸ)</span></li>
                    <li><strong>(l)</strong> = Liquid <span class="punjabi">(ਤਰਲ)</span></li>
                    <li><strong>(g)</strong> = Gas <span class="punjabi">(ਗੈਸ)</span></li>
                    <li><strong>(aq)</strong> = Aqueous (dissolved in water) <span class="punjabi">(ਜਲਮਈ ਘੋਲ)</span></li>
                </ul>
                <div class="equation">Ca(OH)₂(aq) + CO₂(g) &rarr; CaCO₃(s)↓ + H₂O(l)</div>
                <p><em>Note: The ↓ arrow also indicates a precipitate (solid) was formed! The &uarr; arrow indicates a gas.</em></p>
