        <h3 style="margin-top:0; color: var(--goku-blue); font-size: 2rem;">The Magic of Litmus</h3>
        <div class="reading-text" id="read-ch2a">Long before digital pH meters existed, ancient chemists relied on nature to reveal the invisible world of acids and bases. They discovered that certain natural dyes changed color depending on the environment. The most famous of these is litmus, a purple dye extracted from lichens—a slow-growing plant-like organism found on rocks and trees. When placed in an acidic solution, this purple dye instantly flushes to a bright red. When dropped into a basic solution, it turns a deep, vibrant blue. This simple biological extract gave early scientists the power to 'see' the chemical nature of a liquid simply by watching its color shift.</div>
