        <h3 style="margin-top:0; color: var(--goku-blue); font-size: 2rem;">The Acid Rain Crisis</h3>
        <div class="reading-text" id="read-ch2b">When fossil fuels like coal and petroleum are burned in factories and vehicles, they release large amounts of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides into the atmosphere. These toxic gases float high into the sky and mix with atmospheric moisture. A chemical reaction occurs, transforming the water droplets into dilute sulfuric and nitric acids. When this moisture falls back to Earth, it is called acid rain. Normal rain is slightly acidic with a pH around 5.6, but acid rain drops significantly lower. As this highly acidic water flows into lakes and rivers, it lowers the pH of the entire body of water, making it nearly impossible for sensitive aquatic life, like fish and frogs, to survive.</div>
    </div>
