        <h3 style="margin-top:0; color: var(--goku-blue); font-size: 2rem;">The Baking Soda Volcano</h3>
        <div class="reading-text" id="read-ch2c">If you have ever mixed vinegar and baking soda together to make a fake science-fair volcano, you have witnessed an acid-carbonate reaction firsthand. Vinegar contains ethanoic acid, and baking soda is sodium hydrogencarbonate. When they meet, the acid breaks apart the carbonate molecule, instantly releasing water and a massive surge of carbon dioxide gas. This sudden release of gas causes the bubbling eruption. Bakers use this exact same chemical principle to make cakes. By mixing baking soda with a mild edible acid, carbon dioxide bubbles get trapped in the wet dough. When the cake bakes, the gas expands, forcing the dough to rise and become light and fluffy!</div>
