        <h3 style="margin-top:0; color: var(--goku-blue); font-size: 2rem;">The Anodizing Shield</h3>
        <div class="reading-text" id="read-ch3a">Aluminum is a fascinating metal. By all chemical logic, it is highly reactive and should corrode away quickly in the open air. However, aluminum has a secret weapon. The moment raw aluminum touches oxygen, it reacts instantly to form a microscopic, transparent skin of aluminum oxide. Unlike iron rust, which flakes off and exposes more metal to destruction, this aluminum oxide skin sticks tightly to the surface like a waterproof shield. It completely blocks any more oxygen from getting in. Modern engineers purposely use electricity to make this oxide shield even thicker, a process called anodizing, which makes aluminum parts nearly indestructible against the weather.</div>
