                <h2>The Chlor-Alkali Process <span class="pyq-tag">PSEB 2020, 2022</span></h2>
                <p>When electricity is passed through an aqueous solution of sodium chloride (called brine), it decomposes to form sodium hydroxide.</p>
                <div class="equation">2NaCl(aq) + 2H₂O(l) &rarr; 2NaOH(aq) + Cl₂(g) + H₂(g)</div>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Chlorine gas (Anode):</strong> Used for water treatment and swimming pools.</li>
                    <li><strong>Hydrogen gas (Cathode):</strong> Used for fuel and making margarine.</li>
                    <li><strong>Sodium hydroxide (near Cathode):</strong> Used for degreasing metals and making soaps.</li>
                </ul>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Manufacturing Salts: Bleaching Powder & Baking Soda</h2>
                <p><strong>1. Bleaching Powder ($CaOCl_2$):</strong> Produced by the action of chlorine on dry slaked lime.</p>
                <div class="equation">Ca(OH)₂ + Cl₂ &rarr; CaOCl₂ + H₂O</div>
                <p><em>Uses: Disinfecting drinking water, bleaching cotton.</em></p>
                
                <p><strong>2. Baking Soda ($NaHCO_3$):</strong> Produced using sodium chloride, water, $CO_2$, and ammonia.</p>
                <div class="equation">NaCl + H₂O + CO₂ + NH₃ &rarr; NH₄Cl + NaHCO₃</div>
                <p><em>Uses: Making baking powder (which makes cakes fluffy), antacid.</em></p>
