                <h2>Metals Reacting with Water</h2>
                <p>Metals react differently based on their reactivity.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Cold Water <span class="punjabi">(ਠੰਡਾ ਪਾਣੀ)</span>:</strong> Sodium ($Na$) and Potassium ($K$) react violently. The reaction is so exothermic the evolved hydrogen catches fire! Calcium reacts less violently and floats.</li>
                    <li><strong>Hot Water <span class="punjabi">(ਗਰਮ ਪਾਣੀ)</span>:</strong> Magnesium ($Mg$) reacts gently and floats.</li>
                    <li><strong>Steam Only <span class="punjabi">(ਸਿਰਫ਼ ਭਾਫ਼)</span>:</strong> Aluminum ($Al$), Iron ($Fe$), and Zinc ($Zn$). They don't react with liquid water at all.</li>
                    <li><strong>No Reaction:</strong> Lead, Copper, Silver, Gold.</li>
                </ul>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Metals Reacting with Acids <span class="punjabi">(ਤੇਜ਼ਾਬਾਂ ਨਾਲ ਧਾਤਾਂ ਦੀ ਕਿਰਿਆ)</span></h2>
                <p>Generally: <span class="equation">Metal + Dilute Acid &rarr; Salt + Hydrogen Gas</span></p>
                
                <div class="pitfall-box">
                    <h3>🚨 The Nitric Acid Anomaly</h3>
                    <p>Hydrogen gas is <strong>NOT</strong> evolved when a metal reacts with Nitric Acid ($HNO_3$).</p>
                    <p><strong>Why?</strong> $HNO_3$ is a strong oxidizing agent. It oxidizes the $H_2$ produced to water ($H_2O$) and itself gets reduced to nitrogen oxides (like $NO_2$ or $NO$).</p>
                    <p><em>(Only Magnesium and Manganese react with very dilute $HNO_3$ to give $H_2$ gas.)</em></p>
                </div>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Metallurgy: The 3 Stages</h2>
                <p>Minerals are compounds naturally found in the earth. If a mineral contains a very high percentage of metal that can be extracted profitably, it is an <strong>Ore</strong>. Dirt and sand mixed in are called <strong>Gangue</strong>.</p>
                <ol>
                    <li><strong>Enrichment of Ore:</strong> Removing the gangue using physical or chemical separation methods.</li>
                    <li><strong>Extraction of Metal:</strong> Getting the raw metal out of the ore (depends on reactivity).</li>
                    <li><strong>Refining:</strong> Purifying the extracted metal.</li>
                </ol>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Extraction Based on Reactivity</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Low Reactivity (e.g., Mercury, Copper):</strong> Can be reduced to metals by heating alone in air.<br>
                    <span class="equation">2HgS + 3O₂ &rarr; 2HgO + 2SO₂</span> (then heat HgO to get Hg)</li>
                    <li><strong>Medium Reactivity (e.g., Zinc, Iron):</strong> First converted to oxides (by roasting/calcination), then reduced using Carbon (coke).</li>
                    <li><strong>High Reactivity (e.g., Sodium, Aluminum):</strong> Cannot be reduced by carbon. They are extracted by <strong>Electrolytic Reduction</strong> (electricity passed through molten ore).</li>
                </ul>
</div></div>
