        <h3 style="margin-top:0; color: var(--goku-blue); font-size: 2rem;">The Thermit Welding Process</h3>
        <div class="reading-text" id="read-ch3b">The thermit reaction is one of the most spectacular and violent displacement reactions in chemistry. When a mixture of iron(III) oxide and aluminum powder is ignited, the highly reactive aluminum forcefully displaces the iron from its oxide. This reaction is intensely exothermic, meaning it releases a massive amount of heat. In fact, so much heat is generated that the iron produced is entirely in a liquid, molten state. Engineers use this specific chemical property to their advantage. They ignite this mixture directly over broken railway tracks, allowing the molten iron to flow into the cracks and weld the heavy steel rails seamlessly together.</div>
