<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Why does Carbon Share? (Reasoning)</h2>
                <p>Carbon has 4 valence electrons (Configuration: 2, 4). To achieve stability (8 electrons), it must gain or lose 4. Why doesn't it form ionic bonds?</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>It cannot gain 4 ($C^{4-}$ anion):</strong> It would be very difficult for the nucleus with 6 protons to hold on to 10 electrons.</li>
                    <li><strong>It cannot lose 4 ($C^{4+}$ cation):</strong> It would require a massive amount of energy to remove 4 electrons leaving a tiny, highly positive nucleus.</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Solution:</strong> It shares valence electrons to form <span class="accent">Covalent Bonds</span>!</p>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Electron Dot Structures <span class="punjabi">(ਇਲੈਕਟ੍ਰਾਨ ਬਿੰਦੂ ਬਣਤਰ)</span></h2>
                <p>These structures show how valence electrons are shared to form covalent bonds.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Hydrogen ($H_2$):</strong> 2 H atoms share 1 pair of electrons (Single bond).</li>
                    <li><strong>Oxygen ($O_2$):</strong> 2 O atoms share 2 pairs of electrons (Double bond).</li>
                    <li><strong>Nitrogen ($N_2$):</strong> 2 N atoms share 3 pairs of electrons (Triple bond).</li>
                    <li><strong>Ammonia ($NH_3$):</strong> 1 N shares electrons with 3 H atoms, leaving one "lone pair" unbonded.</li>
                </ul>
</div></div>
