        <div class="reading-text" id="read-ch4b">By the 1860s, scientists were completely baffled by the structure of Benzene. They knew its formula was C6H6, but they could not figure out how six carbon atoms and six hydrogen atoms could possibly link together using standard straight chains. The legend goes that the German chemist August Kekulé fell asleep by the fire and began dreaming of molecules twisting like snakes. Suddenly, one of the snakes grabbed its own tail, forming a spinning circle. Kekulé woke up with a flash of insight: the six carbon atoms of Benzene were not in a straight line, but formed a closed hexagonal ring! This dream unlocked the entire field of aromatic chemistry.</div>
