        <h3 style="margin-top:0; color: var(--goku-blue); font-size: 2rem;">The Soap Tug-of-War</h3>
        <div class="reading-text" id="read-ch4c">Washing a greasy shirt requires a fascinating chemical tug-of-war. Soap molecules are long chains with two very different ends. One end is the hydrophilic head, which loves water and bonds easily with it. The other end is the hydrophobic tail, which completely repels water but acts like a magnet for oils and dirt. When you put soap in water, the tails hide from the water by burrowing into the greasy dirt, while the heads stick out into the surrounding water. This creates a spherical structure called a micelle. As the washing machine agitates the water, the hydrophilic heads are pulled by the water currents, tearing the dirt away from the fabric and washing it down the drain.</div>
