<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Early Classification: Dobereiner's Triads</h2>
                <p>When elements are arranged in order of increasing atomic masses, groups of three elements (triads) with similar properties are found.</p>
                <p><strong>Rule:</strong> The atomic mass of the middle element is roughly the average of the atomic masses of the other two elements.</p>
                <h3>Example: The Alkali Metal Triad</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Lithium (Li) = 7</li>
                    <li>Sodium (Na) = 23</li>
                    <li>Potassium (K) = 39</li>
                </ul>
                <p><em>Average of Li and K = (7 + 39) / 2 = <strong>23</strong> (which is Sodium!)</em></p>
                <div class="pitfall-box">
                    <h3>🚨 Limitation</h3>
                    <p>He could only identify three triads from the elements known at that time.</p>
                </div>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Newlands' Law of Octaves</h2>
                <p>He arranged the known elements in order of increasing atomic mass. He found that the properties of every eighth element were similar to that of the first (like musical notes).</p>
                <div class="pitfall-box">
                    <h3>🚨 Limitations</h3>
                    <ol>
                        <li>It was applicable <strong>only up to Calcium</strong>. After that, the 8th element did not match.</li>
                        <li>He assumed only 56 elements existed in nature and no more would be found.</li>
                        <li>He placed dissimilar elements (like Cobalt and Nickel) in the same slot to fit the table.</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>
</div></div>
