        <h3 style="margin-top:0; color: var(--goku-blue); font-size: 2rem;">Mendeleev's Bold Gamble</h3>
        <div class="reading-text" id="read-ch5a">Dmitri Mendeleev is remembered as a genius not just for what he put into his periodic table, but for what he left out. While arranging the known elements by their atomic masses, Mendeleev realized that the pattern occasionally broke. Instead of forcing elements into the wrong groups, he boldly left empty gaps in his table. He confidently predicted that these gaps belonged to elements that simply had not been discovered yet. For instance, he left a space under Aluminum and temporarily named the missing element Eka-Aluminum. Years later, scientists discovered the metal Gallium, and its physical and chemical properties matched Mendeleev's predictions almost perfectly, proving the profound power of his periodic classification.</div>
    </div>
    </div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Mendeleev's Hidden Genius <span class="pyq-tag">PSEB 2019, 2023</span></h2>
                <p>Mendeleev famously left gaps in his table for elements that had not yet been discovered. He even predicted their properties!</p>
                <table>
                    <tr>
                        <th>Mendeleev's Predicted Name</th>
                        <th>Actual Element Discovered Later</th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Eka-Boron</td>
                        <td>Scandium (Sc)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Eka-Aluminum</td>
                        <td>Gallium (Ga)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Eka-Silicon</td>
                        <td>Germanium (Ge)</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>
                <p><em>(Eka is a Sanskrit prefix meaning "one" or "first")</em></p>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Mendeleev's Anomalies <span class="punjabi">(ਖਾਮੀਆਂ)</span></h2>
                <p>Mendeleev's table was great, but it had a few unsolvable problems:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Position of Hydrogen:</strong> It resembles both Alkali metals (Group 1) and Halogens (Group 17).</li>
                    <li><strong>Position of Isotopes:</strong> Isotopes have the same chemical properties but different masses. They would need separate slots in a mass-based table, ruining the layout.</li>
                    <li><strong>Wrong Mass Order:</strong> Sometimes he had to put slightly heavier elements before lighter ones (e.g., Cobalt before Nickel) to match chemical properties.</li>
                </ul>
</div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box"><h2>Reading Comprehension <span class="pyq-tag" style="background:#4F46E5;">Story Mode</span></h2>
    <div class="reading-box">
