        <h3 style="margin-top:0; color: var(--goku-blue); font-size: 2rem;">Moseley's X-Ray Revolution</h3>
        <div class="reading-text" id="read-ch5b">In 1913, a brilliant 25-year-old physicist named Henry Moseley conducted a ground-breaking experiment. He fired a stream of electrons at various metal targets and measured the X-rays they emitted. He discovered that the frequency of the X-rays was mathematically tied to the amount of positive charge inside the atom's nucleus—a value we now call the Atomic Number. This proved that elements should be sorted by their atomic number, not their atomic mass! Moseley's genius instantly solved the flaws in Mendeleev's table. Tragically, just two years later, Moseley was killed in World War I, but his atomic number legacy forever shaped the modern periodic table.</div>
    </div>
    </div></div>
<div class="slide"><div class="content-box">
                <h2>Solving Mendeleev's Problems</h2>
                <p>The Modern Periodic Table (developed by Henry Moseley) solved Mendeleev's anomalies:</p>
                <div class="template-box">
                    <h3>⚖️ Connecting the Law</h3>
                    <p>The <strong>Modern Periodic Law</strong> states that properties depend on Atomic Number, not Mass. This instantly solved the Isotope problem because all isotopes of an element have the <em>exact same atomic number</em>, meaning they only take up one slot! It also fixed the Cobalt/Nickel order.</p>
                </div>
</div></div>

