        <h3 style="margin-top:0; color: var(--goku-blue); font-size: 2rem;">The Zig-Zag Line</h3>
        <div class="reading-text" id="read-ch5c">If you look at the right side of the Modern Periodic Table, you will notice a strange, staircase-like line drawn between the elements. This zig-zag line acts as the border wall between two warring nations: the Metals on the left and the Non-Metals on the right. But the elements sitting exactly on this border, like Silicon, Germanium, and Arsenic, refuse to pick a side. They are called Metalloids. They look shiny like metals but are brittle like non-metals. Most importantly, they do not conduct electricity well enough to be metals, but they aren't insulators either. They are 'semiconductors'. This single property allows us to control the flow of electricity precisely, making metalloids the fundamental building blocks of all computer chips, smartphones, and modern technology.</div>
